review_blob: Purchased in London from Saliburys Golders Green.  Small head, low carbonination. Pleasant citrius aroma. Good hop spicyness with citrus bending with the sweet malts, a lingering bitter finish. Really enjoyed this bottled beer served at around 15C, nice to taste the hops.

From the bottle, pours with a good head that laces down the glass. Estery/malty nose, with a rich malt (crystal/caramel and slight roast/choc) flavour, and smooth finish.  The bottle I had was a clean skin and very fresh, making for an enjoyable ale.
beer_name: Sunshine Coast Robinsons Old Dark Ale

review_blob: A lager with a slight honey and fresh chilli flavour. The head is white and laces down the glass.  Leaves a pleasent chilli burn on the tougue.  The chilli is balanced with the base lager. If you dont like chillis then this is not for you.

Poured from the bottle, the head was a non event, hardly got a look in.  The aroma is roasty,  the flavour is a big whack of roasted barley balnced with a slight sweetness and with a hint of chocolate malt. I didnt find it thin, having  more body than a Guiness Foreign Extra stout, but without the mellow complexity of a Coopers Foriegn Extra stout. With a bit of age this would a good stout.
A lager with a honey flavour that almost drowns out the hop flavour,  hop finish and anything else. Lacks the crispness of a lager, but the  hop flavour is enjoyable (POR?).

Have drunk this beer for a number of years. At 5.8 ABV this makes a eventfull session beer. The bottled version needs to be gently inverted to mix in the yeast before opening and pouring. Slight banana esters and spicy POR hops temp the nose. The body is a little thin if the bottle is not inverted prior to pouring. The fluffy head disappears but laces the glass as you refresh yourself. The slight bitter finsh balances the sweetness. The draft version lacks the bottling yeast and can be a little thinner.
